# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actinophryid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actinophryid/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:actinophryid/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:actinophryid/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:actinophryid/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:actinophryid/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The **actinophryids** are an order of heliozoa, a polyphyletic array of amoebae.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] They are common in fresh water and occasionally found in marine and soil habitats.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Actinophryids are unicellular and roughly spherical in shape, with many axopodia that radiate outward from the cell body.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Axopodia are a type of pseudopodia that are supported by hundreds of microtubules arranged in interlocking spirals and forming a needle-like internal structure or axoneme.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Small granules, extrusomes, that lie under the membrane of the body and axopodia capture flagellates, ciliates and small metazoa that make contact with the arms.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Actinophryids are largely aquatic protozoa with a spherical cell body and many needle-like axopodia.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] They resemble the shape of a sun due to this structure, which is the inspiration for their common name: heliozoa, or "sun-animalcules".
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Their bodies, without arms, range in size from a few tens of micrometers to slightly under a millimeter across.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The outer region of cell body is often vacuolated.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The endoplasm of actinophryids is less vacuolated than the outer layer, and a sharp boundary layer may be seen by light microscopy.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The organisms can be either mononucleate, with a single, well defined nucleus in the center of the cell body, or multinucleate, with 10 or more nuclei located under the outer vacuolated layer of cytoplasm.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The cytoplasm of actinophryids is often granular, similar to that of *Amoeba*.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Actinophryid cells may fuse when feeding, creating larger aggregated organisms.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Fine granules that occur just under the cell membrane are used up when food vacuoles form to enclose prey.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Actinophryids may also form cysts when food is not readily available.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] A layer of siliceous plates is deposited under the cell membrane during the encystment process.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are common in these organisms, which are presumed to use them to maintain body volume by expelling fluids to compensate for the entry of water by osmosis.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are visible as clear bulges from the surface of the cell body that slowly fill then rapidly deflate, expelling their contents into the environment.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The most distinctive characteristic of the actinophryids is their axopodia.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] These axopodia consist of a central, rigid rod which is coated in a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] In *Actinophrys* the axonemes end on the surface of the central nucleus, and in the multicellular *Actinosphaerium* they end at or near nuclei.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The axonemes are composed of microtubules arranged in a double spiral pattern characteristic of the order.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Due to their long, parallel construction, these microtubules demonstrate strong birefringence.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] These axopodia are used for prey capture, in movement, cell fusion and perhaps division.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] They are stiff but may flex especially near their tips, and are highly dynamic, undergoing frequent construction and destruction.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] When used to collect prey items, two methods of capture have been noted, termed axopodial flow and rapid axopodial contraction.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Axopodial flow involves the slow movement of a prey item along the surface of the axopod as the ectoplasm itself moves, while rapid axopodial contraction involves the collapse of the axoneme's microtubule structure.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] This behavior has been documented in many species, including *Actinosphaerium nucleofilum*, *Actinophrys sol*, and *Raphidiophrys contractilis*.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The rapid axopodial contraction occurs at high speed, often in excess of 5mm/s or tens of body lengths per second.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The axopodial contractions have been shown to be highly sensitive to environmental factors such as temperature and pressure as well as chemical signals like Ca2+ and colchicine.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Reproduction in actinophryids generally takes place via fission, where one parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] For multinucleate heliozoa, this process is plasmotomic as the nuclei are not duplicated prior to division.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] It has been observed that reproduction appears to be a response to food scarcity, with an increased number of divisions following the removal of food and larger organisms during times of food excess.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Actinophryids also undergo autogamy during times of food scarcity.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] This is better described as genetic reorganization than reproduction, as the number of individuals produced is the same as the initial number.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Nonetheless, it serves as a way to increase genetic diversity within an individual which may improve the likelihood of expressing favorable genetic traits.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Plastogamy has also been extensively documented in actinophryids, especially in multinucleate ones.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* were observed to combine freely without the combination of nuclei, and this process sometimes resulted in more or less individuals than originally combined.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] This process is not caused merely by contact between two individuals but can be caused by damage to the cell body.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Under unfavourable conditions, some species will form a cyst.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] This is often the product of autogamy, in which case the cysts produced are zygotes.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Cells undergoing this process withdraw their axopodia, adhere to the substrate, and take on an opaque and grayish appearance.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] This cyst then divides until only uninucleate cells remain.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] The cyst wall is thickly layered 7–8 times and includes gelatinous layers, layers of silica plates, and iron.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Originally placed in Heliozoa (Sarcodina), the actinophryids are now understood to be part of the stramenopiles.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] They are unrelated to centrohelid and desmothoracid heliozoa with which they had been previously classified.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] There are several genera included within this classification.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] *Actinophrys* are smaller and have a single, central nucleus.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] Most have a cell body 40–50 micrometer in diameter with axopods around 100 μm in length, though this varies significantly.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* are several times larger, from 200 to 1000 μm in diameter, with many nuclei and are found exclusively in fresh water.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] A third genus, *Camptonema*, has a debated status.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] It has been observed once and was treated as a junior subjective synonym of *Actinosphaerium* by Mikrjukov & Patterson in 2001, but as a valid genus by Cavalier-Smith & Scoble (2013).
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] *Heliorapha* is a further debated taxon, it being a new generic vehicle for the species *azurina* that was initially assigned to the genus *Ciliophrys*.
[src:actinophryid/actinophryid] According to the latest review of actinophryid classifications, they are organized into two genera and six species.
[src:actinophryid/actinophrys] There are currently four accepted species of *Actinophrys*.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] The cytoplasm of *Actinosphaerium* species is divided into a highly vacuolated ectoplasm (i.e. with numerous non-contractile vacuoles) and a less vacuolated endoplasm.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] Multiple long, slender axopodia radiate out of the cell body.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] Each axopodium is composed of a relatively stiff axial rod, surrounded by a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] The rods penetrate deep into the endoplasm and can terminate freely or close to the cell nuclei.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] In 1965, Hovasse divided *Actinosphaerium* to create the genus *Echinosphoerium* or *Echinosphaerium* (both spellings were used in his work).
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] He introduced this name for actinosphaerids whose axopodia terminated on the surface of nuclei (specifically *A. eichhornii*), on the assumption that in *Actinosphaerium* the axopodia do not end on nuclei.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] However, the original description of *Actinosphaerium* by Stein in 1857 mentions no details on this feature.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] Studies of the ultrastructure of actinosphaerids around the same era showed that some axopodia do end on the nuclei, but not always.
[src:actinophryid/actinosphaerium] There are currently two accepted species in the genus.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] AlgaeBase began in March 1996, founded by Michael Guiry.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] By 2005, the database contained about 65,000 names.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] In 2013, AlgaeBase and the Flanders Marine Institute (VLIZ) signed an end-user license agreement regarding the Electronic Intellectual Property of AlgaeBase.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] This allows the World Register of Marine Species (WoRMS) to include taxonomic names of algae in WoRMS, thereby allowing WoRMS, as part of the Aphia database, to make its overview of all described marine species more complete.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] After a long phase of further development and testing, the AlgaeBase harvester tool was implemented by the WoRMS data management team in early 2019.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] Since then, newly-added species in AlgaeBase are added to Aphia and, if marine, to WoRMS as well.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] The database is hosted at the National University of Ireland's Ryan Institute, in Galway.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] It includes about all types of algae, as well as one group of flowering plants, the sea-grasses.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] Information about each species' taxonomy, nomenclature and distribution is included, and the algae covered include terrestrial as well as marine and freshwater species, such as seaweeds, phytoplankton, and freshwater algae.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] As of 2019, marine species have the best coverage, including sea-grasses.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] As of 2014 there were nearly 17,000 images, and the database was being used by 2,000–3,000 individual visitors each day.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] As of 2023, there were about 170,000 species and infraspecies in AlgaeBase.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] The synchronisation between AlgaeBase and Aphia was possible through support of the LifeWatch Species Information Backbone.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] LifeWatch, the E-Science European Infrastructure for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Research, is a distributed virtual laboratory, which is used for different aspects of biodiversity research.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] As of 2022, the main sponsors of the database are the Phycological Society of America, the British Phycological Society, the International Phycological Society, and the Korean Phycological Society.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] Programming is carried out by Pier Kuipers and Caoilte Guiry, and Michael Guiry.
[src:actinophryid/algaebase] Jonathan Guthrie was responsible for programming much of earlier versions.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Algospongia (vernacular name: algosponges) is a taxon of calcified fossil organisms comprising around 90 accepted genera and several hundred species, treated taxonomically as a single class in an unspecified phylum.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Originally considered to be fossil sponges or "pseudo algae", an assignment now refuted, their taxonomic position is somewhat unresolved.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Of the three most prominent recent researchers, B.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Mamet (Belgium) assigns certain families (e.g.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Palaeoberesellaceae, Beresellaceae and Issinellaceae) to Chlorophyta (green algae) as an order of that phylum (Palaeosiphonocladales), at least one other family (Ungdarellaceae) to Rhodophyta (red algae), and some other genera (*Groenlandella*, *Labyrinthoconus*) simply to "Microproblematica".
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Cózar (Spain) treated Algospongia (such as the family Calcifoliaceae) as Algae *incertae sedis*, before deciding (in 2010) against any algal affinity and reassigning them to the [zoological] protists, as a group possibly paralleling the Foraminifera.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Since that paper, Cózar has continued to use zoological terminology in his published works, while Vachard has once again assigned the group to the Algae *incertae sedis*, lying hypothetically mid-way between the extant Rhodophyta and Chlorophyta.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] A number of the genera allocated to Algospongia in the present treatment (which follows Vachard & Cózar, 2010 in the main) were recently (2021) treated as either Foraminifera, or as red or green algae, in the World Register of Marine Species, a situation that is currently under revision.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Members of the group occur in the fossil record from the Ordovician to the Late Permian periods, although only *Wetheredella* is prominent prior to the start of the Devonian.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] Algosponges are described as a group of sessile or attached microorganisms with characteristic calcified walls described as "yellowish, apparently granular" that are frequently perforated, and possess either lateral or terminal apertures between successive chambers or cells.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] The treatment below is based on that published by Vachard & Cózar in 2010, (alternative, botanical treatment indicated separated by "/"); more recent genera (post 2010) and, in some cases, corrections have been added per other available sources.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] The possibly analogous Foraminifera (protists or Protozoa in many classifications) are members of the clade SAR, which is presently assigned to the kingdom Chromista in many classifications.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] The stratigraphic range of selected algosponge genera is summarised in Figure 15 of Vachard & Cózar (2010).
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] From this Figure it is apparent that *Wetheredella* is the sole representative of the group from the Upper Ordovician through the Silurian, being joined by *Asphaltinoides* a little before the Silurian ends.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] The majority of other genera then develop within, and/or are restricted to, the Devonian through Carboniferous periods, with a relatively small number (16) persisting through the Permian before all becoming extinct by the end of that period.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] The same authors also comment (their "Conclusion" no.
[src:actinophryid/algospongia] As mentioned above, members of the claimed single class Algospongia have been assigned to different taxonomic groups over time, with no clear consensus emerging.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The **alveolates** are a group of protists, considered a major clade or superphylum within Eukaryota.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] They are currently grouped with the Stramenopiles and Rhizaria among the protists with tubulocristate mitochondria into the SAR supergroup.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The most notable shared characteristic is the presence of cortical (near the surface) alveoli (sacs).
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] These are flattened vesicles (sacs) arranged as a layer just under the membrane and supporting it, typically contributing to a flexible pellicle (thin skin).
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] In armored dinoflagellates they may contain stiff plates.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Alveolates have mitochondria with tubular cristae (invaginations), and cells often have pore-like intrusions through the cell surface.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The group contains free-living and parasitic organisms, predatory flagellates, and photosynthetic organisms.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Almost all sequenced mitochondrial genomes of ciliates and apicomplexa are linear.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The mitochondria almost all carry mtDNA of their own but with greatly reduced genome sizes.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Exceptions are *Cryptosporidium* which are left with only a mitosome, the circular mitochondrial genomes of *Acavomonas* and *Babesia microti*, and *Toxoplasma*'s highly fragmented mitochondrial genome, consisting of 21 sequence blocks which recombine to produce longer segments.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The relationship of apicomplexa, dinoflagellates and ciliates had been suggested during the 1980s, and this was confirmed in the early 1990s by comparisons of ribosomal RNA sequences, most notably by Gajadhar *et al*.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith introduced the formal name Alveolata in 1991, although at the time he considered the grouping to be a paraphyletic assemblage.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Many biologists prefer the use of the colloquial name 'alveolate'.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Alveolata include around six major groups.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The Acavomonidia and Colponemidia were previously grouped together as colponemids, a taxon now split because each has a distinctive organization or ultrastructural identity.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The Acavomonidia are closer to the dinoflagellate/perkinsid group than the Colponemidia are.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] As such, the informal term "colponemids", as it stands currently, covers two non-sister groups within Alveolata: the Acavomonidia and the Colponemidia.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] As of present, five genera of colponemids are recognized.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The Apicomplexa and dinoflagellates may be more closely related to each other than to the ciliates.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Both have plastids, and most share a bundle or cone of microtubules at the top of the cell.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] In apicomplexans this forms part of a complex used to enter host cells, while in some colorless dinoflagellates it forms a peduncle used to ingest prey.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Various other genera are closely related to these two groups, mostly flagellates with a similar apical structure.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] These include free-living members in *Oxyrrhis* and *Colponema*, and parasites in *Perkinsus*, *Parvilucifera*, *Rastrimonas* and the ellobiopsids.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] In 2001, direct amplification of the rRNA gene in marine picoplankton samples revealed the presence of two novel alveolate lineages, called group I and II.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Group I has no cultivated relatives, while group II is related to the dinoflagellate parasite *Amoebophrya*, which was classified until now in the Syndiniales dinoflagellate order.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Some studies suggested the haplosporids, mostly parasites of marine invertebrates, might belong here, but they lack alveoli and are now placed among the Cercozoa.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The ellobiopsids are of uncertain relation within the alveolates.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Silberman et al 2004 establish that the *Thalassomyces* genus of ellobiopsids are alveolates using phylogenetic analysis, however as of 2016 no more certainty exists on their place.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The development of plastids among the alveolates is intriguing.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Cavalier-Smith proposed the alveolates developed from a chloroplast-containing ancestor, which also gave rise to the Chromista (the chromalveolate hypothesis).
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Other researchers have speculated that the alveolates originally lacked plastids and possibly the dinoflagellates and Apicomplexa acquired them separately.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] However, it now appears that the alveolates, the dinoflagellates, the Colpodellida and the heterokont algae acquired their plastids from a red alga with evidence of a common origin of this organelle in all these four clades.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] A Bayesian estimate places the evolution of the alveolate group at ~850 million years ago.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The Alveolata consist of Myzozoa, ciliates, and colponemids.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] In other words, the term Myzozoa, meaning "to siphon the contents from prey", may be applied informally to the common ancestor of the subset of alveolates that are neither ciliates nor colponemids.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Predation upon algae is an important driver in alveolate evolution, as it can provide sources for endosymbiosis of novel plastids.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The term Myzozoa is therefore a handy concept for tracking the history of the alveolate group.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The ancestors of the alveolate group may have been photosynthetic.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] The ancestral alveolate probably possessed a plastid.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Chromerids, apicomplexans, and peridinin dinoflagellates have retained this organelle.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] In one school of thought the common ancestor of the dinoflagellates, apicomplexans, *Colpodella*, Colpodellida, and *Voromonas* was a myzocytotic predator with two heterodynamic flagella, micropores, trichocysts, rhoptries, micronemes, a polar ring and a coiled open sided conoid.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] While the common ancestor of alveolates may also have possessed some of these characteristics, it has been argued that Myzocytosis was not one of these characteristics, as ciliates ingest prey by a different mechanism.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] An ongoing debate concerns the number of membranes surrounding the plastid across apicomplexans and certain dinoflagellates, and the origin of these membranes.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] This ultrastructural character can be used to group organisms and if the character is in common, it can imply that phyla had a common photosynthetic ancestor.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Ciliates are a model alveolate, having been genetically studied in great depth over the longest period of any alveolate lineage.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] They are unusual among eukaryotes in that reproduction involves a micronucleus and a macronucleus.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Their reproduction is easily studied in the lab, and made them a model eukaryote historically.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Being entirely predatory and lacking any remnant plastid, their development as a phylum illustrates how predation and autotrophy are in dynamic balance and that the balance can swing one way or other at the point of origin of a new phylum from mixotrophic ancestors, causing one ability to be lost.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Few algae have been studied for epigenetics.
[src:actinophryid/alveolate] Those for which epigenetic data are available include some algal alveolates.
